BBWI reported 2Q25 adj. EPS of \(\) 0.37\(= (Street),\) \text {driven by (i) +1.5\% revenue growth (vs. mgmt's Flat to +2\% guidance), (ii) gross margin expansion of +30bps Y/Y to 41.3\% (vs Street 41.2\%), and (iii) SG&A rate of 30.2\% (vs. Street 29.9\%) equating to an 11.1\% operating margin (vs. Street 11.3\%)}. Importantly, 2Q's +1.5\% revenue growth marked the fourth consecutive quarter of underlying sales growth, including positive dual- channel traffic and +low- single- digit mix- adjusted AUR increases, noting favorable customer response to the Semi- Annual Sale, Father's Day campaign, and new sanitizer product launches.

Looking ahead, management raised the low end of the FY26 adj. EPS outlook to \(\) 3.35-\ \(3.60 (vs.\) \ \(3.25 -\) 3.60 prior & vs. Street \(\) 3.47\() based on a narrowed revenue growth outlook of +1.5\% to +2.7\% (vs. prior +1 - 3\% Y / Y and bracketing Street +2.2\%), gross margin of - 44\% (vs. Street 44.1\%) and adj. SG&A rate of - 27.7\% (vs. - 27.5\% prior and Street 27\%), equating to operating margin of - 16.7\% at the midpoint on our estimates ( = Street). In addition, management raised the FY25 share repurchase outlook to\) \ \(400M\) (vs. \(\) 300M\(prior).

On 3Q25: Management guided 3Q EPS to \(\) 0.37- 3.45\(below Street\) \ \(0.49\) based on revenues \(+1\%\) to \(+3\%\) Y/Y (vs. Street \(+1.7\%)\) , gross margin of \(- 42.2\%\) (below Street 42.8\%), or down - 130bps YOY, primarily driven by a - 240bps ( \(\) 40M\(tariff cost related headwind) with the quarter impacted by inventory subject to the 145\% China tariff rate, partially offset by favorability on merchandise margins & fulfillment cost leverage, and SG&A rate deleverage of - 160bps Y/Y to - 31.5\% (vs. Street 30.4\%) on higher healthcare and technology costs alongside strategic investments, translating into a - 10.7\% operating margin (below Street 12.4\%)

For 4Q25: Management's guidance implies 4Q EPS of \(\) 2.12\( (vs. Street\) \ \(2.29\) based on revenues \(+2\%\) Y/Y (vs. Street \(+1.7\%\) Y/Y) and operating margin down - 30bps Y/Y at the midpoint to 24.0\% (vs. Street 23.1\%)

(1) Current.3QTD/August Business "on Track" with 3Q's \(+1 - 3\%\) Revenue Growth Outlook: Mgmt cited current trends 3Q to date (August) are currently "on track" achieve 3Q's \(+1 - 3\%\) revenue growth outlook. To this point, management clarified that messaging on the conference call was not intended to imply that an acceleration relative to August/QTD is required to achieve 3Q's \(+1 - 3\%\) revenue growth outlook (a point we see formally clarified next week). Importantly, management cited 3 key incremental revenue growth drivers in 3Q, including (i) the Disney Villains collaboration, which launches early access to loyalty members this week (with the global launch date 9/3) building on the success of the 1Q Disney Princess collection; (ii) fall product innovation/ marketing (including initial packaging/marketing enhancements to Body Care &

We rate BBWI Overweight. The combination of (i) consistent low- single- digit revenue growth and incremental acceleration opportunities within adjacencies or through collaborations, (ii) expanding high- teens operating margins, and (iii) visible shareholder returns with \(\) 825M+\(of FCF generation annually supporting a consistent dividend yield & share repurchase programme supports our OW rating.

Our Dec '26 price target of \(\) 46\(is unchanged and based on 7.3x our FY27 EBITDA estimate, supported by our linear regression analysis of BBWI's fundamental top/bottom- line profile relative to Non- Distressed Retail peers.

Aromatherapy); and (iii) a single fragrance launched among at the end of the quarter. Putting this into perspective, the Disney Villain collection by our linear math supports a \(+80bp\) lift to revenue growth to total 3Q on the 3Qproportion SKU collection (vs. \(1Q25\) s \(\sim 200bp\) lift to revenue growth associated with the Disney Princess collection at 85 products).

(2) Breaking Down 3Q's Gross Margin Outlook = Underlying Merchandise Margin Expansion: Near term, management guided 3Q gross margin to decline -130bps Y/Y to \(-42.2\%\) (vs. Street \(42.8\%\) ), reflecting a \(-240bp\) headwind associated with \(\)40M\(of incremental tariff costs, with the quarter negatively impacted by inventory subject to the\)145\%\(China tariff rate. Partial offsets include: (i) B&O leverage associated with the exit of a third-party fulfillment center (quantified as a -30bps tailwind) & (ii) underlying merchandise margin expansion (implied +80bps YOY), consistent with underlying merchandise margin expansion achieved in each of 1Q & 2Q supported by favorability on AURs (+LSD% mix-adjusted through 1H25) & improved price/promotional mix. Taking this a step further - management noted opportunity multi-year under CEO Heaf to further improve merchandise margins over time through improved marketing/messaging to the consumer regarding product innovation & attributes (rather than leading with price).

(3) FY25 = Confirmed Operating Margin "Trough" w/ FY26 Expansion Drivers: Mgmt's FY25 implied operating margin outlook calls for a \(\sim 16.7\%\) margin at the midpoint, or down \(\sim 70\) bps YOY. Breaking down the build: (i) \(\sim 115\) bp tariff headwind associated with \(\)85M\(of tariff headwinds, net of mitigation, & (ii) SG&A de leverage of -80bps on +2.1\%\) revenue growth at the midpoint, which compares \(\sim 10\) bps of leverage implied by mgmt's historical 2.5-3.5% fixed cost leverage point, pointing to \(\sim 70\) bps worth of elevated SG&A expenses in FY25 associated with higher healthcare costs & strategic investments (i.e. CEO Heaf's decision to fast-track no-regret initiatives to accelerate revenue growth, which included the use of external consultants = 1x cost), partially offset by (i) \(\sim 30\) bps of favorability associated with the exit of a third-party fulfillment center & (ii) \(\sim 90\) bps of underlying merchandise margin expansion. Importantly, management cited 4 key drivers supporting operating margin expansion YOY in FY26 relative to FY25's \(\sim 16.7\%\) base, including (1) YOY dual tailwind from tariffs, as FY26 will no longer be burdened by \(145\%\) China tariff rates nor Canada reciprocal tariffs based on current trade policy; (2) revenue growth acceleration opportunity under CEO Heaf (packaging/labeling, marketing, digital, distribution) with a firm commitment to cost discipline holding the fixed cost leverage points in the business at 2.5-3.5% revenue growth supporting favorability on flow-through on revenue growth upside; (3) YOY tailwind within SG&A expenses cycling 1x costs associated with the leadership transition/strategic investments (i.e. consulting fees); and (4) continued opportunity to drive improved merchandise margins over time (w/ FY25, by our math, already executing \(\sim 90\) bps of improvement in merchandise margin expansion YOY). Said differently - our build points to FY25 operating margin as the model "trough" - with opportunity for FY26 operating margin to deliver "at least" the Street's pre-print assumption of \(+15\) bps of YOY expansion.

Model Implications: We model FY25 EPS of \(\) 3.48\(vs. Street\) \ \(3.44\) and FY26 EPS of \(\) 3.85\(vs. Street\) \ \(3.76\) . We maintain our Overweight rating and December '26 price target of \(\) 46\(based on\) \sim 7x\$ our FY27E EBITDA.

- 2Q Top/Bottom-Line Breakdown: BBWI reported 2Q revenues \(+1.5\%\) Y/Y (vs. Flat to \(+2\%\) Y/Y guidance), which compares to 1Q's underlying \(-1\%\) growth rate (excluding DIS) and 4Q's \(+0.6\%\) underlying growth (excluding the 53rd week), and reflects the fourth quarter of underlying sales growth. Specifically, management cited the primary drivers of the \(+1.5\%\) 2Q sales growth as low-single-digit mix-adjusted AUR increases and positive traffic growth (ahead of third-party benchmarks) with the semi-annual sale driving strong customer engagement. By category, 2Q revenue growth was led by positive growth in (i) Soaps & Sanitizers up \(+HSD\% (= 1Q + MSD\%)\), with the sanitizer

business outperforming relative to total store on strength in 1oz sanitizer sprays & Pocketbacs; (ii) Home Fragrance up +LSD% (≥1Q +LSD%), with strength in single wick candles, wallflowers, and home sprays; and (iii) Body care down-LSD ($ in Millions (except per share)ActualJPMEConsensusRevenue$1,549$1,563$1,553Gross Profit$640$646$639SG&A$468$467$464Operating Income$172$180$176Interest Expense$68$74$79Net Income$78$82$79Shares Outstanding (M)211212212EPS$0.37$0.38$0.37Margins and GrowthRevenue Growth1.5%2.4%1.8%Gross Margin41.3%41.4%41.2%SG&A Rate30.2%29.9%29.9%EBIT Margin11.1%11.5%11.3%Tax Rate29.1%29.0%28.5%
